    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5f1edeba-1877-43f8-bd3f-bb70ec3c3bc1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 5-year-old girl brought to clinic by her mother in the early winter after 3 days of nasal congestion, runny nose, sneezing, sore throat, intermittent dry cough, and a mild stomach ache that seems worse when her appetite is poor. She appears tired but interactive, sitting on her mother’s lap with a box of tissues and occasionally rubbing her nose. Her cheeks are mildly flushed, and she has a hoarse voice with frequent sniffles. She is drinking small amounts of water and juice, though her appetite is reduced compared with usual.\n\nAt baseline, {patientName} is an active kindergarten student who enjoys drawing, playground games, and pretend tea parties with her stuffed animals. She lives with both parents and an older brother who recently had a similar cold, and several classmates have also had coughs and runny noses. The family has a stable home environment, no tobacco exposure indoors, and a pet cat. She attends school regularly and participates in dance classes once a week, with frequent close contact with other children during school and indoor activities in cold weather.\n\nOver the past few days, her mother reports low-grade fever at home, restless sleep due to nasal obstruction, mild throat discomfort when swallowing, and occasional complaints that her tummy hurts, without vomiting or diarrhea. There has been no labored breathing, wheezing, rash, ear drainage, or lethargy. She remains consolable and playful in short bursts but tires more easily than usual. Urination is normal, suggesting preserved hydration.\n\n{patientName} is appropriately grown for age, weighing 20 kg, with clean clothing and good hygiene. She is up to date on routine childhood immunizations. Her family describes her as generally healthy, social, and energetic, with close relationships to her parents, brother, grandparents, and classmates."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:515d9fbe-b2bd-435f-9b6e-2d0127ce7822",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has mild intermittent allergic rhinitis, which can contribute to nasal mucosal irritation and may increase susceptibility to symptomatic upper respiratory infections during high-exposure seasons, but she has no chronic cardiopulmonary disease and no prior diagnosis of asthma. She was born at term without neonatal complications and has met developmental milestones appropriately. Her past illnesses have been limited to occasional uncomplicated viral colds and one episode of acute otitis media at age 3 treated successfully as an outpatient. She has never been hospitalized. Her renal and hepatic function are presumed normal based on age, absence of chronic disease, normal urine output, no jaundice, and no history of kidney or liver disorder.\n\nHer mother reports symptom onset 3 days ago after exposure to several children with cough and runny noses at school and an older sibling recovering from a similar acute upper respiratory infection. Since onset, {patientName} has had nasal congestion, clear rhinorrhea, sneezing, scratchy throat, mild dry cough, mild stomach ache, and a maximum recorded temperature of 38.1 Cel at home. She has had mildly decreased appetite but continues to drink fluids, with no vomiting or diarrhea.\n\nShe takes no daily prescription medications other than cetirizine as needed during allergy flares, which may reduce rhinorrhea from allergies but would not cause this illness. Over-the-counter acetaminophen has been given intermittently for fever and discomfort. There is no smoke exposure at home. Because she is a kindergarten student with frequent close contact, shared classroom materials, and indoor group activities, she has regular exposure to common viral respiratory pathogens. She also attends dance class, another setting with close child-to-child contact during respiratory virus season. There is no known immune deficiency, and no recent travel, animal bites, or unusual environmental exposures. The family seeks evaluation because of persistent congestion and poor sleep, but they deny respiratory distress, cyanosis, drooling, neck stiffness, or altered mental status.\n\nFamily members have a pattern of typical viral colds during the winter months, including her older brother with a recent acute upper respiratory infection this week, supporting household exposure. Her mother also notes that {patientName} tends to develop more nasal symptoms during allergy seasons, though she is otherwise healthy."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
